  "prompt": "How early should I start ACT prep?",
  "response": "The ideal timeline for starting ACT prep can vary depending on several factors, including your current level of preparedness, your target score, and your overall schedule. However, here are some general guidelines:\n\n1. **Begin Early (Junior Year)**: Many students start seriously preparing for the ACT during their junior year of high school, ideally around the fall or winter. This allows ample time to study and take the exam more than once if needed.\n\n2. **Summer Before Junior Year**: If you\u2019re motivated and want to get a head start, consider beginning prep during the summer before your junior year. This can help you build a strong foundation and become familiar with the test format.\n\n3. **Regular Study Periods**: Aim for consistent, shorter study sessions (e.g., several hours each week) rather than cramming. Spreading out your study time helps with retention and reduces stress.\n\n4. **Take a Diagnostic Test Early**: If possible, take a practice test early in your prep process to identify your strengths and weaknesses. This can help you focus your study efforts more effectively.\n\n5. **Consider Your Schedule**: Factor in other commitments, such as schoolwork, extracurricular activities, and family obligations, when deciding how early to start studying.\n\n6. **Plan for Retakes**: Many students take the ACT more than once to improve their scores. Starting early gives you the flexibility to retake the test if needed.\n\nIn summary, starting your ACT prep at least six months before your test date is generally a good rule of thumb. Adjust based on your individual circumstances and comfort level with the material.",
